{"id":"1305.5168","submitter":"Javaraiah Javaraiah Dr.","authors":"J. Javaraiah","title":"Long-term temporal variations in the areas of sunspot groups","comments":"14 pages, 7 figures, accepted by Advances in Space Research. arXiv\n  admin note: text overlap with arXiv:1208.2862","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.asr.2013.04.029","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Recently, we analyzed the combined Greenwich and Solar Optical Observing\nNetwork (SOON) sunspot group data during the period 1874-2011 and studied\nvariations in the annual numbers of small, large and big sunspot groups. Here\nthat analysis is extended and studied variations in the mean maximum sizes (the\nmean values of maximum areas) of the aforementioned three classes of sunspot\ngroups and also their combination. It is found that there is no significant\ncorrelation between the mean maximum size of any class of sunspot groups and\nthe International Sunspot Number (Rz), probably due to in a given time interval\nsmall sunspot groups/sunspots outnumber the large ones. A pattern of an\napproximate 9-year period cycle is seen in the variations of the mean maximum\nsizes of the large and the big sunspot groups during a solar cycle. On\nlong-time scales it is found that there exists a strong 130 or more years cycle\nin the variation of the mean size of the small sunspot groups, whereas there is\na hint on the existence of approximate 44-year cycles in the variations of the\nmean maximum sizes of the large and the big sunspot groups. During the decline\nphase of cycle 23, there was a scarcity in the very small sunspot groups\n(maximum area AM < or = 37 msh), which may be related to the slow growth of\nsunspot groups during this period. During the minimum between cycles 23 and 24\nmay be due to the presence of a number of small sunspot groups whose AM > 37\nmsh was larger than that of whose AM < or = 37 msh, the relatively large size\ncoronal holes were present at low-latitudes and the total solar irradiance was\nvery low.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 2 May 2013 08:29:02 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 14 Jun 2013 09:57:57 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 26 Jul 2013 11:06:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-07-29"}
